style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: times new roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-
WEIGHT: normal">The purpose of this Amendment No. 1 to&#160;Westmountain Index 
Advisor, Inc. Quarterly Report on Form 10-Q for the quarterly period ended July 
31, 2012, filed with the Securities and Exchange Commission on&#160;September 
11, 2012&#160;&#160;(the &#8220;Form 10-Q&#8221;), is solely to furnish Exhibit 
101 to the Form 10-Q in accordance with Rule 405 of Regulation S-T. Exhibit 101 
to this report provides the consolidated financial statements and related notes 
from the Form 10-Q formatted in XBRL (eXtensible Business Reporting 
Language).</font></font></div>
<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 
0pt" align="center"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-WEIGHT:

0pt" align="left"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-WEIGHT: bold"><font 
style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: times new roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-
WEIGHT: normal">No other changes have been made to the Form 10-Q. This Amendment
No. 1 to the Form 10-Q speaks as of the original filing date of the Form 10-Q, 
does not reflect events that may have occurred subsequent to the original filing
date, and does not modify or update in any way disclosures made in the original 
Form 10-Q.</font></font></div>
<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT:

WEIGHT: normal">Pursuant to Rule 406T of Regulation S-T, the interactive data 
files on Exhibit 101 hereto are deemed not filed or part of a registration 
statement or prospectus for purposes of Sections 11 or 12 of the Securities Act 
of 1933, as amended, are deemed not filed for purposes of Section 18 of the

    <us-gaap:BusinessDescriptionAndBasisOfPresentationTextBlock 
contextRef="From2011-11-01to2012-07-31">&lt;p style="margin: 
0pt"&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 8pt/normal Times New Roman, 
Times, Serif; margin: 0"&gt;The Company acquired Terra Mining Corporation 
(&amp;#147;TMC&amp;#148;)&#13;on February 28, 2011 and accounted for the 
transaction as a reverse acquisition using the purchase method of accounting, 
whereby&#13;TMC is deemed to be the accounting acquirer (legal acquiree) and 
WMTN to be the accounting acquiree (legal acquirer). The 
Company&amp;#146;s&#13;financial statements before the date of Share Exchange 
are those of TMC with the results of WMTN being consolidated from the 
date&#13;of Share Exchange. The equity section and earnings per share have been 
retroactively restated to reflect the reverse acquisition&#13;and no goodwill 
has been recorded. The Company adopted TMC&amp;#146;s fiscal year, which is 
October 31.&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 8pt/normal Times New Roman, 
Times, Serif; margin: 0"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 
8pt/normal Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0"&gt;WMTN is an exploration 
and development stage company that&#13;explores, acquires, and develops advanced
stage properties.&lt;b&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/b&gt;The Company has a high-grade gold 
system in the resource&#13;definition phase with 168,000 oz of inferred gold 
which in total offers potential of 1,000,000 ounces that is owned by the 
Company&amp;#146;s&#13;wholly owned subsidiary, TMC. The property consists of 
344 Alaska state mining claims covering approximately 85 square miles. 
All&#13;Government permits and reclamation plans for continued exploration 
through 2014 were renewed in 2010,&amp;#160;which is referred 
to&#13;as&amp;#160;the &amp;#147;TMC project&amp;#148;.&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p
style="font: 8pt/normal Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 
0"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 8pt/normal Times New 
Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0"&gt;The Company&amp;#146;s primary activity will 
be to proceed with&#13;the TMC project and other mining opportunities that may 
present themselves from time to time. The Company cannot guarantee that&#13;the 
TMC project will be successful or that any project that WMTN embarks upon will 
be successful. The goal is to build our Company&#13;into a successful mineral 
exploration and development Company.&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 
8pt/normal Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 
0"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 8pt/normal Times New 
Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0"&gt;The Company has budgeted expenditures for the
next twelve&#13;months of approximately $2,600,000, depending on additional 
financing, for general and administrative expenses and exploration&#13;and 
development to implement the business plan as described 
below.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 8pt/normal 
Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p
style="font: 8pt/normal Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0"&gt;WMTN 
believes it will have to raise substantial additional&#13;capital in order to 
fully implement the business plan.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;If economic reserves of 
gold and/or other minerals are proven,&#13;additional capital will be needed to 
actually develop and mine those reserves. The Company must expend $6,750,000 for
a total of&#13;$9,050,000 plus option payments of $450,000 over the next three 
years as an &amp;#147;earn in&amp;#148; on the TMC project to own rights&#13;to 
80% of the project.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;Even if economic reserves are found, if 
the Company is unable to raise this capital, the Company&#13;will not be able to
complete the earn in on this 
project.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 8pt/normal 
Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p
style="font: 8pt/normal Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0"&gt;The 
Company&amp;#146;s principal source of liquidity for the&#13;next several years 
will need to be the continued raising of capital through the issuance of equity 
or debt.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;WMTN plans&#13;to raise funds for each step of the 
project and as each step is successfully completed, raise the capital for the 
next phase.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;WMTN&#13;believes this will reduce the cost of 
capital as compared to trying to raise all the anticipated capital at once up 
front.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;However,&#13;since WMTN&amp;#146;s ability to raise
additional capital will be affected by many factors, most of which are not 
within the Company&amp;#146;s&#13;control (see &amp;#147;Risk 
Factors&amp;#148;), no assurance can be given that WMTN will in fact be able to 
raise the additional capital&#13;as it is needed.&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p 
style="font: 8pt/normal Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 
0"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 8pt/normal Times New 
Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0"&gt;The Company may choose to scale back 
operations to operate&#13;at break-even with a smaller level of business 
activity, while adjusting overhead depending on the availability of additional 
financing.&#13;In addition, the Company expects that it will need to raise 
additional funds if the Company decides to pursue more rapid 
expansion,&#13;appropriate responses to competitive pressures, or the 
acquisition of complementary businesses or technologies, or if it must 
respond&#13;to unanticipated events that require it to make additional 
investments. The Company cannot assure that additional financing will&#13;be 
available when needed on favorable terms, or at all.&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p 
style="font: 8pt/normal Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 
0"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 8pt/normal Times New 
Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0"&gt;The Company&amp;#146;s accountants have 
expressed doubt about&#13;the Company&amp;#146;s ability to continue as a going 
concern as a result of its history of net loss. The Company&amp;#146;s 
ability&#13;to achieve and maintain profitability and positive cash flow is 
dependent upon our ability to successfully execute the plans to&#13;pursue the 
TMC project as described in this Form 10-Q. The outcome of these matters cannot 
be predicted at this time. These consolidated&#13;financial statements do not 
include any adjustments to the amounts and classifications of assets and 
liabilities that might be&#13;necessary should the Company be unable to continue
its business.&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 8pt/normal Times New Roman, 
Times, Serif; margin: 0"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 
8pt/normal Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0"&gt;The accompanying 
unaudited consolidated financial statements&#13;of WestMountain and its 
subsidiaries have been prepared in accordance with generally accepted accounting
principles (&amp;#147;GAAP&amp;#148;)&#13;for interim financial information and 
with the instructions to Form 10-Q and Article 10 of Regulation S-X. 
Accordingly, they do&#13;not include all of the information and footnotes 
required by U.S. GAAP for complete financial statements. The financial 
statements&#13;for the periods July 31, 2012 and 2011 are unaudited and include 
all adjustments necessary to a fair statement of the results of&#13;operations 
for the periods then ended. All such adjustments are of a normal, recurring 
nature. The results of the Company&amp;#146;s&#13;operations for any interim 
period are not necessarily indicative of the results of the Company&amp;#146;s 
operations for a full fiscal&#13;year. For further information, refer to the 
financial statements and footnotes thereto included in the Company&amp;#146;s 
Annual Report&#13;on Form 10-K for the fiscal year ended October 31, 2011 as 
filed with the Securities and Exchange Commission (the 
&amp;#147;SEC&amp;#148;)&#13;on December 20, 
2011.&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="margin: 
0pt"&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</us-gaap:BusinessDescriptionAndBasisOfPresentationTextBlock>
    <us-gaap:SignificantAccountingPoliciesTextBlock contextRef="From2011-11-
01to2012-07-31">&lt;p style="margin: 0pt"&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p 
style="font: 8pt/normal Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0"&gt;This 
summary of significant accounting policies is presented&#13;to assist in 
understanding the Company&amp;#146;s consolidated financial statements. The 
financial statements and notes are representations&#13;of the Company&amp;#146;s
management, which is responsible for their integrity and 
objectivity.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;These accounting policies&#13;conform to 
accounting principles generally accepted in the United States of America, and 
have been consistently applied in the&#13;preparation of the financial 
statements.&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 8pt/normal Times New Roman, 
Times, Serif; margin: 0"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 
8pt/normal Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0"&gt;&lt;u&gt;Accounting 
Method&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 8pt/normal Times New 
Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0"&gt;The Company&amp;#146;s financial statements 
are prepared using&#13;the accrual basis of accounting in accordance with
accounting principles generally accepted in the United States of 
America.&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 8pt/normal Times New Roman, 
Times, Serif; margin: 0"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 
8pt/normal Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0"&gt;&lt;u&gt;Principles of 
Consolidation&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 8pt/normal Times 
New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0"&gt;These consolidated financial statements 
include our consolidated&#13;financial position, results of operations, and cash
flows. All material intercompany balances and transactions have been 
eliminated&#13;in the accompanying consolidated financial 
statements.&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 8pt/normal Times New Roman, 
Times, Serif; margin: 0"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 
8pt/normal Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0"&gt;&lt;u&gt;Foreign 
Currency Translation&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 8pt/normal 
Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0"&gt;The consolidated financial 
statements are presented in US&#13;dollars, which is the parent 
company&amp;#146;s and its subsidiary&amp;#146;s functional currency and the 
Company&amp;#146;s presentation&#13;currency. Transactions in foreign currencies
are initially recorded in the functional currency at the rate in effect at the 
date&#13;of the transaction.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;Monetary assets and liabilities 
denominated in foreign currencies are retranslated at the spot rate&#13;of 
exchange in effect at the reporting date. All differences are taken to the 
consolidated statement of operations and comprehensive&#13;loss. Non-monetary 
items that are measured in terms of historical cost in a foreign currency are 
translated using the exchange&#13;rate at the date of the initial 
transaction.&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 8pt/normal Times New Roman, 
Times, Serif; margin: 0"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 
8pt/normal Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0"&gt;&lt;u&gt;Cash and Cash 
Equivalents&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 8pt/normal Times New
Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0"&gt;The Company classifies highly liquid 
temporary investments&#13;with an original maturity of three months or less when
purchased as cash equivalents. The Company maintains cash balances at 
various&#13;financial institutions. Balances at US banks are insured by the 
Federal Deposit Insurance Corporation up to $250,000. Beginning&#13;December 31,
2010 and through December 31, 2012, all noninterest-bearing transaction accounts
are fully insured, regardless of&#13;the balance of the account, at all FDIC-
insured institutions. The Company has not experienced any losses in such 
accounts and believes&#13;it is not exposed to any significant risk for cash on 
deposit.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;As of July 31, 2012, the Company had no uninsured 
cash&#13;amounts.&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 8pt/normal Times New 
Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p 
style="font: 8pt/normal Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 
0"&gt;&lt;u&gt;Equipment&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 
8pt/normal Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0"&gt;Equipment consists of 
machinery, furniture and fixtures and&#13;software, which are stated at cost 
less accumulated depreciation and amortization. Depreciation is computed by the 
straight-line&#13;method over the estimated useful lives or lease period of the 
relevant asset, generally 3-5 years.&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 
8pt/normal Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 
0"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 8pt/normal Times New 
Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0"&gt;&lt;u&gt;Mineral 
Properties&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 8pt/normal Times New 
Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0"&gt;Costs of acquiring mineral properties are 
capitalized by project&#13;area upon purchase of the associated claims. Costs to
maintain the mineral rights and leases are expensed as 
incurred.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;When&#13;a property reaches the production stage, 
the related capitalized costs will be amortized, using the units of production 
method&#13;on the basis of periodic estimates of ore 
reserves.&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 8pt/normal Times New Roman, 
Times, Serif; margin: 0"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 
8pt/normal Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0"&gt;Mineral properties are 
periodically assessed for impairment&#13;of value and any diminution in 
value.&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 8pt/normal Times New Roman, Times, 
Serif; margin: 0"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 8pt/normal
Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0"&gt;The Company has access to the camp
by airplane. There is no&#13;road access from camp to the project area where 
drilling and bulk sampling mining occurs. It is approximately 1 1/2 miles 
from&#13;camp to the project area.&amp;#160; Power generation is by diesel 
generator at the camp. Fuel is brought in for 
the&amp;#160;generators&amp;#160;by&#13;a cargo plane to the 
airstrip.&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 8pt/normal Times New Roman, 
Times, Serif; margin: 0"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 
8pt/normal Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0"&gt;&lt;u&gt;Long-Lived 
Assets&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 8pt/normal Times New 
Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0"&gt;The Company reviews its long-lived assets for
impairment when&#13;changes in circumstances indicate that the carrying amount 
of an asset may not be recoverable. Long-lived assets under 
certain&#13;circumstances are reported at the lower of carrying amount or fair 
value. Assets to be disposed of and assets not expected to provide&#13;any 
future service potential to the Company are recorded at the lower of carrying 
amount or fair value (less the projected cost&#13;associated with selling the 
asset). To the extent carrying values exceed fair values, an impairment loss is 
recognized in operating&#13;results.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;As of July 31, 2012, 
there are no impairments recognized.&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 
8pt/normal Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 
0"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 8pt/normal Times New 
Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0"&gt;&lt;u&gt;Alaska Reclamation and Remediation 
Liabilities&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 8pt/normal Times New
Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0"&gt;The Company operates in Alaska. The State of 
Alaska Department&#13;of Natural Resources requires a pool of funds from all 
permittees with exploration and mining projects to cover reclamation. 
There&#13;is a $750 per acre disturbance reclamation bond that is required for 
disturbance of 5 acres or more and/or removal of more the&#13;50,000 cubic yards
of material. The Company does not expect to exceed the 
minimum&amp;#160;requirements&amp;#160;and is not expected to&#13;be required to
file a&amp;#160;reclamation&amp;#160;bond until the project advances 
and&amp;#160;feasibility&amp;#160;justifies expansion.&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p 
style="font: 8pt/normal Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 
0"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 8pt/normal Times New 
Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0"&gt;The Company expects to record reclamation 
bond as a liability&#13;in the period in which the Company is required to pay a 
reclamation bond. A corresponding asset is also recorded and 
depreciated&#13;over the life of the asset. After the initial measurement of the
asset retirement obligation, the liability will be adjusted at&#13;the end of 
each reporting period to reflect changes in reclamation 
bond.&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 8pt/normal Times New Roman, Times, 
Serif; margin: 0"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 8pt/normal
Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0"&gt;&lt;u&gt;Mineral Exploration and 
Development Costs&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 8pt/normal 
Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0"&gt;All exploration expenditures are 
expensed as incurred.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;Significant&#13;property acquisition 
payments for active exploration properties are 
capitalized.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;If no minable ore body is 
discovered,&#13;previously capitalized costs are expensed in the period the 
property is abandoned.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;Expenditures to develop new 
mines,&#13;to define further mineralization in existing ore bodies, and to 
expand the capacity of operating mines, are capitalized and amortized&#13;on a 
unit of production basis over proven and probable 
reserves.&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 8pt/normal Times New Roman,
 Times, Serif; margin: 0"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 
8pt/normal Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0"&gt;Should a property be 
abandoned, its capitalized costs are&#13;charged to 
operations.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;The Company charges to operations the allocable 
portion of capitalized costs attributable to&#13;properties 
abandoned.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;Capitalized costs are allocated to properties sold
based on the proportion of claims sold to the&#13;claims remaining within the 
project area.&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 8pt/normal Times New Roman, 
Times, Serif; margin: 0"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 
8pt/normal Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0"&gt;&lt;u&gt;Net Loss Per
Share&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 8pt/normal Times New 
Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0"&gt;Basic loss per common share is computed by 
dividing net loss&#13;available to common shareholders by the weighted average 
number of shares of common stock outstanding for the periods 
presented.&#13;Diluted net loss per share reflects the potential dilution that 
could occur if securities or other contracts to issue common stock&#13;were 
exercised or converted into common stock or resulted in the issuance of common 
stock that would then share in the income of&#13;the Company, subject to anti-
dilution limitations. As of July 31, 2012, the Company had warrants for the 
purchase of 7,294,796&#13;common shares and 385,000 common shares related 
promissory notes to which were considered but were not included in the 
computation&#13;of loss per share at July 31, 2012 because they would have been 
anti-dilutive. As of July 31, 2011, the Company had warrants for&#13;the 
purchase of 4,861,095 common shares which were considered but were not included 
in the computation of loss per share at July&#13;31, 2011 because they would 
have been anti-dilutive.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;In addition, the Company has 500,000
shares of common stock to&#13;be issued over three years to International Tower 
Hill Ltd. which could potentially dilute future earnings per 
share.&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 8pt/normal Times New Roman, Times, 
Serif; margin: 0"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 8pt/normal
Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0"&gt;&lt;u&gt;Prepaid 
Expenses&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 8pt/normal Times New 
Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0"&gt;Prepaid expenses were $200,542 and $238,860 
as of July 31,&#13;2012 and October 31, 2011, respectively. The 
account&amp;#160;&amp;#160;reflects expenses&amp;#160;&amp;#160;that have 
been&amp;#160;&amp;#160;prepaid&#13;and are being amortized over the life of the
service agreements.&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 8pt/normal Times New 
Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p 
style="font: 8pt/normal Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 
0"&gt;&lt;u&gt;Use of Estimates&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 
8pt/normal Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0"&gt;The preparation of 
financial statements in conformity with&#13;accounting principles generally 
accepted in the United States requires management to make estimates and 
assumptions that affect&#13;the reported amounts of assets and liabilities and 
disclosure of contingent assets and liabilities at the date of the 
financial&#13;statements and the reported amounts of revenues and expenses 
during the reporting period. Actual results could differ from 
those&#13;estimates.&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 8pt/normal Times New 
Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p 
style="font: 8pt/normal Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 
0"&gt;&lt;u&gt;Recent Accounting 
Pronouncements&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 8pt/normal Times 
New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p 
style="font: 8pt/normal Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0"&gt;A variety 
of proposed or otherwise potential accounting standards&#13;are currently under 
study by standard setting organizations and various regulatory agencies. Due to 
the tentative and preliminary&#13;nature of those proposed standards, management
has not determined whether implementation of such proposed standards would be 
material&#13;to the consolidated financial 
statements.&amp;#160;&lt;b&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&#13;&#13;
&lt;p style="margin: 0pt"&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</us-
gaap:SignificantAccountingPoliciesTextBlock>
    <us-gaap:BasisOfAccountingPolicyPolicyTextBlock contextRef="From2011-11-
01to2012-07-31">&lt;p style="font: 8pt/normal Times New Roman, Times, Serif; 
margin: 0"&gt;&lt;u&gt;Accounting Method&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p 
style="font: 8pt/normal Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0"&gt;The 
Company&amp;#146;s financial statements are prepared using&#13;the accrual basis
of accounting in accordance with accounting principles generally accepted in the
United States of America.&lt;/p&gt;</us-
gaap:BasisOfAccountingPolicyPolicyTextBlock>
    <us-gaap:ConsolidationPolicyTextBlock contextRef="From2011-11-01to2012-07-
31">&lt;p style="font: 8pt/normal Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 
0"&gt;&lt;u&gt;Principles of Consolidation&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p 
style="font: 8pt/normal Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0"&gt;These
consolidated financial statements include our consolidated&#13;financial 
position, results of operations, and cash flows. All material intercompany 
balances and transactions have been eliminated&#13;in the accompanying 
consolidated financial statements.&lt;/p&gt;</us-
gaap:ConsolidationPolicyTextBlock>
    <us-gaap:ForeignCurrencyTransactionsAndTranslationsPolicyTextBlock 
contextRef="From2011-11-01to2012-07-31">&lt;p style="font: 8pt/normal Times New 
Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0"&gt;&lt;u&gt;Foreign Currency 
Translation&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 8pt/normal Times New
Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0"&gt;The consolidated financial statements are 
presented in US&#13;dollars, which is the parent company&amp;#146;s and its 
subsidiary&amp;#146;s functional currency and the Company&amp;#146;s 
presentation&#13;currency. Transactions in foreign currencies are initially 
recorded in the functional currency at the rate in effect at the date&#13;of the
transaction.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;Monetary assets and liabilities denominated in 
foreign currencies are retranslated at the spot rate&#13;of exchange in effect 
at the reporting date. All differences are taken to the consolidated statement 
of operations and comprehensive&#13;loss. Non-monetary items that are measured 
in terms of historical cost in a foreign currency are translated using the 
exchange&#13;rate at the date of the initial transaction.&lt;/p&gt;</us-
gaap:ForeignCurrencyTransactionsAndTranslationsPolicyTextBlock>
    <us-gaap:CashAndCashEquivalentsPolicyTextBlock contextRef="From2011-11-
01to2012-07-31">&lt;p style="font: 8pt/normal Times New Roman, Times, Serif; 
margin: 0"&gt;&lt;u&gt;Cash and Cash 
Equivalents&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 8pt/normal Times New
Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0"&gt;The Company classifies highly liquid 
temporary investments&#13;with an original maturity of three months or less when
purchased as cash equivalents. The Company maintains cash balances at 
various&#13;financial institutions. Balances at US banks are insured by the 
Federal Deposit Insurance Corporation up to $250,000. Beginning&#13;December 31,
2010 and through December 31, 2012, all noninterest-bearing transaction accounts
are fully insured, regardless of&#13;the balance of the account, at all FDIC-
insured institutions. The Company has not experienced any losses in such 
accounts and believes&#13;it is not exposed to any significant risk for cash on 
deposit.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;As of July 31, 2012, the Company had no uninsured 
cash&#13;amounts.&lt;/p&gt;</us-gaap:CashAndCashEquivalentsPolicyTextBlock>
    <us-gaap:PropertyPlantAndEquipmentImpairment contextRef="From2011-11-
01to2012-07-31">&lt;p style="font: 8pt/normal Times New Roman, Times, Serif; 
margin: 0"&gt;&lt;u&gt;Equipment&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font:
8pt/normal Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0"&gt;Equipment consists of 
machinery, furniture and fixtures and&#13;software, which are stated at cost 
less accumulated depreciation and amortization. Depreciation is computed by the 
straight-line&#13;method over the estimated useful lives or lease period of the 
relevant asset, generally 3-5 years.&lt;/p&gt;</us-
gaap:PropertyPlantAndEquipmentImpairment>
    <WMTN:MineralPropertiesTextBlock contextRef="From2011-11-01to2012-07-
31">&lt;p style="font: 8pt/normal Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 
0"&gt;&lt;u&gt;Mineral Properties&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p 
style="font: 8pt/normal Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0"&gt;Costs of 
acquiring mineral properties are capitalized by project&#13;area upon purchase 
of the associated claims. Costs to maintain the mineral rights and leases are 
expensed as incurred.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;When&#13;a property reaches the 
production stage, the related capitalized costs will be amortized, using the 
units of production method&#13;on the basis of periodic estimates of ore 
reserves.&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 8pt/normal Times New Roman, 
Times, Serif; margin: 0"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 
8pt/normal Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0"&gt;Mineral properties are 
periodically assessed for impairment&#13;of value and any diminution in 
value.&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 8pt/normal Times New Roman, Times, 
Serif; margin: 0"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 8pt/normal
Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0"&gt;The Company has access to the camp 
by airplane. There is no&#13;road access from camp to the project area where 
drilling and bulk sampling mining occurs. It is approximately 1 1/2 miles 
from&#13;camp to the project area.&amp;#160; Power generation is by diesel
generator at the camp. Fuel is brought in for 
the&amp;#160;generators&amp;#160;by&#13;a cargo plane to the 
airstrip.&lt;/p&gt;</WMTN:MineralPropertiesTextBlock>
    <us-gaap:AssetRetirementObligationsAndEnvironmentalCostPolicyTextBlock 
contextRef="From2011-11-01to2012-07-31">&lt;p style="font: 8pt/normal Times New 
Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0"&gt;&lt;u&gt;Long-Lived 
Assets&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 8pt/normal Times New 
Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0"&gt;The Company reviews its long-lived assets for
impairment when&#13;changes in circumstances indicate that the carrying amount 
of an asset may not be recoverable. Long-lived assets under 
certain&#13;circumstances are reported at the lower of carrying amount or fair 
value. Assets to be disposed of and assets not expected to provide&#13;any 
future service potential to the Company are recorded at the lower of carrying 
amount or fair value (less the projected cost&#13;associated with selling the 
asset). To the extent carrying values exceed fair values, an impairment loss is 
recognized in operating&#13;results.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;As of July 31, 2012, 
there are no impairments recognized.&lt;/p&gt;</us-
gaap:AssetRetirementObligationsAndEnvironmentalCostPolicyTextBlock>
    <WMTN:AlaskaReclamationAndRemediationLiabilitiesTextBlock 
contextRef="From2011-11-01to2012-07-31">&lt;p style="font: 8pt/normal Times New 
Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0"&gt;&lt;u&gt;Alaska Reclamation and Remediation 
Liabilities&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 8pt/normal Times New
Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0"&gt;The Company operates in Alaska. The State of 
Alaska Department&#13;of Natural Resources requires a pool of funds from all 
permittees with exploration and mining projects to cover reclamation. 
There&#13;is a $750 per acre disturbance reclamation bond that is required for 
disturbance of 5 acres or more and/or removal of more the&#13;50,000 cubic yards
of material. The Company does not expect to exceed the 
minimum&amp;#160;requirements&amp;#160;and is not expected to&#13;be required to
file a&amp;#160;reclamation&amp;#160;bond until the project advances 
and&amp;#160;feasibility&amp;#160;justifies expansion.&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p 
style="font: 8pt/normal Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 
0"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 8pt/normal Times New 
Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0"&gt;The Company expects to record reclamation 
bond as a liability&#13;in the period in which the Company is required to pay a 
reclamation bond. A corresponding asset is also recorded and 
depreciated&#13;over the life of the asset. After the initial measurement of the
asset retirement obligation, the liability will be adjusted at&#13;the end of 
each reporting period to reflect changes in reclamation 
bond.&lt;/p&gt;</WMTN:AlaskaReclamationAndRemediationLiabilitiesTextBlock>
    <WMTN:MineralExplorationAndDevelopmentCostsTextBlock contextRef="From2011-
11-01to2012-07-31">&lt;p style="font: 8pt/normal Times New Roman, Times, Serif; 
margin: 0"&gt;&lt;u&gt;Mineral Exploration and Development 
Costs&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 8pt/normal Times New 
Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0"&gt;All exploration expenditures are expensed as 
incurred.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;Significant&#13;property acquisition payments for 
active exploration properties are capitalized.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;If no minable 
ore body is discovered,&#13;previously capitalized costs are expensed in the 
period the property is abandoned.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;Expenditures to develop new
mines,&#13;to define further mineralization in existing ore bodies, and to 
expand the capacity of operating mines, are capitalized and amortized&#13;on a 
unit of production basis over proven and probable 
reserves.&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 8pt/normal Times New Roman, 
Times, Serif; margin: 0"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 
8pt/normal Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0"&gt;Should a property be 
abandoned, its capitalized costs are&#13;charged to 
operations.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;The Company charges to operations the allocable 
portion of capitalized costs attributable to&#13;properties 
abandoned.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;Capitalized costs are allocated to properties sold
based on the proportion of claims sold to the&#13;claims remaining within the 
project area.&lt;/p&gt;</WMTN:MineralExplorationAndDevelopmentCostsTextBlock>

after the closing&#13;of the acquisition of TMC by WMTN and an additional 
250,000 shares of WMTN common stock issued on or before each of December 
31,&#13;2011 and December 31, 2012. The $50,000 due with the signing of the 
Letter of Intent in February 2010 was paid September 17, 2010.&#13;TMC has

the JV Agreement.&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 8pt/normal Times New

style="font: 8pt/normal Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 
0"&gt;&lt;b&gt;Share Exchange Agreement with 
TMC&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 8pt/normal Times New Roman, 
Times, Serif; margin: 0"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 
8pt/normal Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0"&gt;WMTN entered into a 
Share Exchange Agreement with Gregory&#13;Schifrin, American Mining Corporation 
(&amp;#147;AMC&amp;#148;) and James Baughman to acquire 100% of the issued and 
outstanding shares&#13;of common stock of TMC in exchange for 1,500,000 shares 
of restricted common stock of WMTN, par value of $0.001 per 
share.&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 8pt/normal Times New Roman, Times, 
Serif; margin: 0"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 8pt/normal
Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0"&gt;In addition, WMTN issued warrants 
to the TMC founder investors&#13;Gregory Schifrin and James 
Baughman&amp;#160;for 300,000 and 200,000 shares of WMTN common stock, 
respectively. WMTN issued warrants&#13;to other TMC founder investors for 
500,000 shares of common stock. The warrants expire February 17, 2014 and are 
exercisable at&#13;$0.001 per share. WMTN agreed to file a registration 
statement with the SEC with regard to the shares and shares issuable 
upon&#13;exercise of the warrants within ninety days on a best efforts basis. On
June 13, 2011, the warrants were exercised and 1,000,000&#13;shares of WMTN 
common stock were issued.&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 8pt/normal Times
New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p 
style="font: 8pt/normal Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0"&gt;WMTN 
entered into a Share Exchange Agreement with Mining Minerals&#13;LLC (owned 60% 
and 40 % by Gregory Schifrin and James Baughman, respectively) whereby WMTN
acquired the claims recorded with the&#13;Alaska Department of Natural 
Resources, Recording Numbers 2010-000468-0 through 2010-000481-0, recorded on 
October 19, 2010, in&#13;exchange for a total of 5,000,000 shares of common 
stock of WMTN. As of February 18, 2011, the Alaska claims are owned by 
WMTN.&#13;On June 13, 2011, Mining Minerals LLC sold 100,000 shares to Mark 
Scott for $0.001 per share.&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 8pt/normal 
Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p
style="font: 8pt/normal Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 
0"&gt;&lt;b&gt;Other Reverse Merger 
Agreements&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 8pt/normal Times New 
Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p 
style="font: 8pt/normal Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0"&gt;WMTN 
entered into a Consulting Agreement with WestMountain&#13;Asset Management, Inc.
(&amp;#147;WASM and WASM Agreement&amp;#148;), a&amp;#160;WMTN shareholder. 
Under the terms of the WASM Agreement,&#13;WASM agreed to advise WMTN on the 
acquisition of TMC, funding of WMTN and strengthening the WMTN balance sheet 
during the period&#13;ending December 31, 2011. WASM received a Warrant for 
925,000 shares at $0.001 per share.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;The Warrant is in 
substantially&#13;the form and with the terms as contained in Exhibit 10.14 
filed herewith.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;WMTN agreed to file a registration 
statement&#13;with the SEC with regard to the shares issuable upon exercise of 
the warrant within ninety days on a best efforts basis.&amp;#160;On&#13;August 
15, 2011, WASM exercised a portion of the warrant and 866,000 shares of WMTN 
common stock were issued.&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 8pt/normal Times

TMC&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 8pt/normal Times New Roman,

8pt/normal Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0"&gt;On February 18, 2011, 
WMTN entered into a Stock Purchase Agreement&#13;with TMC related to the 
acquisition of Terra Gold Corporation (&amp;#147;TGC&amp;#148;), a wholly owned 
subsidiary of TMC. Under the&#13;terms of the Stock Purchase Agreement, WMTN 
acquired 100% of TGC by assuming $500,000 in debt plus accrued interest of 
$7,685 owed&#13;to BOCO Investments LLC (&amp;#147;BOCO&amp;#148;), an existing 
shareholder in the Company.&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 8pt/normal

style="font: 8pt/normal Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0"&gt;The Company

we&amp;#160;&amp;#160;utilize Minex Mining&#13;contractors for exploration and

31">&lt;p style="margin: 0pt; font: 8pt Times New Roman, Times, 
Serif"&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 8pt/normal Times New Roman, 
Times, Serif; margin: 0"&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;i&gt;Secured Promissory 
Note&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 8pt/normal Times 
New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p
style="font: 8pt/normal Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0"&gt;On August 
8, 2012, the Company, entered into Revolving Credit&#13;Line and Security, 
Secured Convertible Promissory Note and Warrant to Purchase Stock Agreements 
(&amp;#147;Transaction Documents&amp;#148;)&#13;with BOCO Investments, LLC 
(&amp;#147;BOCO&amp;#148;), an existing shareholder in the 
Company.&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 8pt/normal Times New Roman, 
Times, Serif; margin: 0"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 
8pt/normal Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 
0"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 8pt/normal Times New 
Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0"&gt;Under the Transaction Documents, the Company 
issued a Secured&#13;Convertible Promissory Note (&amp;#147;Note&amp;#148;) in 
the principal amount of $1,831,538. The Note is due July 31, 2013 and 
provides&#13;for interest at 15% payable in arrears. The Note and accrued 
interest are convertible into common stock at the lesser of $3.00&#13;or the 
lowest price at which common shares in the Company are issued in any round of 
financing commencing after the date of this&#13;Note and prior to the conversion
discounted price at the discretion of BOCO. The Note is secured by a security 
interest in the&#13;Company&amp;#146;s assets to secure the Company&amp;#146;s 
performance under the Note.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;The Note includes a Note for 
$300,000&#13;dated November 15, 2011 and $400,000 advanced by BOCO during the 
three months ending July 31, 2012. In addition, the Company issued&#13;a Warrant
to purchase 1,250,000 shares of common stock at $0.25. The Warrant expires 
August 7, 2017. There are no registration&#13;requirements. The Transaction 
Documents place certain operating restrictions on the 
Company.&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 8pt/normal Times New Roman, 
Times, Serif; margin: 0"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 
8pt/normal Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0"&gt;The Agreement also 
contains certain representations and warranties&#13;of the Company and BOCO, 
including customary investment-related representations provided by BOCO, as well
as acknowledgements by&#13;BOCO that it has reviewed certain disclosures of the 
Company (including the periodic reports that the Company has filed with 
the&#13;SEC) and that the Company&amp;#146;s issuance of the shares has not been
registered with the SEC or qualified under any state 
securities&#13;laws.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;The Company provided customary 
representations regarding, among other things, its organization, 
subsidiaries,&#13;disclosure reports, absence of certain legal or governmental 
proceedings, financial statements, tax matters, insurance matters,&#13;real 
property and other assets, and compliance with applicable laws and 
regulations.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;BOCO&amp;#146;s representations 
and&#13;warranties are qualified in their entirety (to the extent applicable) by
the Company&amp;#146;s disclosures in the reports it files&#13;with the 
SEC.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;The Company also delivered confidential disclosure 
schedules qualifying certain of its representations&#13;and warranties in 
connection with executing and delivering the Agreement.&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p
style="font: 8pt/normal Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 
0"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 8pt/normal Times New 
Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0"&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;i&gt;Unsecured Promissory 
Notes&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 8pt/normal Times
New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p 
style="font: 8pt/normal Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0"&gt;On February
10, 2012 the Company entered into Promissory Note&#13;Documents with Mark 
Macklin, an existing shareholder in the Company. Under the Promissory Note 
Documents, the Company issued a&#13;Convertible Promissory Note 
(&amp;#147;Macklin Note&amp;#148;) in the principal amount of $100,000. The 
Macklin Note was is due October&#13;10, 2012 and provides for interest at 5% 
payable in arrears. The Macklin Note is convertible into common stock as $1.00 
per share.&#13;In addition, the Company issued 50,000 shares of restricted 
common stock that was expensed to interest at $1.00 per share or 
$50,000&#13;during the three months ended April 30, 
2012.&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 8pt/normal Times New Roman, Times, 
Serif; margin: 0"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 8pt/normal
Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0"&gt;On March 21, 2012 the Company 
entered into Promissory Note&#13;Documents with Fabin Andres and Bill Andres, 
existing shareholders in the Company. Under the Promissory Note Documents, the
Company&#13;issued a Convertible Promissory Note (&amp;#147;Andres 
Notes&amp;#148;) in the principal amount of $100,000 and $100,000, 
respectively.&#13;The Andres Notes are due in twelve months and provide for 
interest at 5% payable in arrears. The Andres Notes are convertible 
into&#13;common stock as $1.00 per share. In addition, the Company issued 50,000
shares of restricted common stock to each party that was&#13;expensed to 
interest at $1.00 per share or $100,000 during the three months ended April 30, 
2012.&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 8pt/normal Times New Roman, Times, 
Serif; margin: 0"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="margin: 0; font:
8pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif"&gt;On April 30, 2012 the Company entered into
Promissory Note Documents with Silver Verde May Mining Company&#13;Inc., a party
related to and existing shareholder and a Director of the Company. Under the 
Promissory Note Documents, the Company&#13;issued a Convertible Promissory Notes
(&amp;#147;SVM Notes&amp;#148;) in the principal amounts of $75,000 and $10,000,
respectively.&#13;The Notes are due in seven months and ten months, 
respectively, and provide for interest at 5% payable in arrears. The SVM 
Notes&#13;are convertible into common stock as $1.00 per share. In addition, the
Company issued 42,500 shares of restricted common stock&#13;that was expensed to
interest at $1.00 per share or $42,500 during the three months ended April 30, 
2012.&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="margin: 0pt; font: 8pt Times New
Roman, Times, Serif"&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</us-gaap:DebtDisclosureTextBlock>

issuances were each exempt from registration under&#13;Section 4(2) of the 
Securities Act of 1933, as amended, as transactions by an issuer not involving a
public offering.&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 8pt/normal Times New 
Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p 
style="font: 8pt/normal Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0"&gt;On January 
24, 2012, the Company issued 60,000 restricted&#13;shares of common stock at 
$.50 per share to Gary Courtney under a Consulting Agreement. The shares do not 
have registration rights.&amp;#160;The&#13;shares were valued at $.50 per share 
and $30,000 was expensed to services during the three months ended January 31, 
2012.&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 8pt/normal Times New Roman, Times,

Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0"&gt;During November and December, 2011,
the Company signed Subscription&#13;Agreements with seven accredited investors 
for $279,601 and issued 101,674 shares of restricted common stock at $2.75 per 
share.&#13;The restricted common stock does not have registration 
rights.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;An amendment to these Subscription Agreements 
signed&#13;in 2011 resulted in an additional issuance of 613,748 shares of 
restricted common stock.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;In addition, the Company 
issued&#13;warrants for 804,701 shares at $2.00 per share. The warrants expire 
February 9, 2015 and do not have registration rights. The warrants&#13;may be 
called by the Company if it has registered the sale of the underlying shares 
with the SEC and a closing price of $4.00 or&#13;more for the Company&amp;#146;s
common stock has been sustained for five trading days. A notice filing under 
Regulation D was filed&#13;with the SEC on December 13 and 23, 2011 and June 7, 
2012 with regard to these stock issuances.&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font:
8pt/normal Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin:

Company issued 7,000 shares of WMTN&#13;restricted common stock to Edward Hall

share.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;The&#13;restricted common stock does not have

Company&#13;if it has registered the sale of the underlying shares with the SEC

does not have registration rights.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;In addition, the Company

shares with the SEC and a closing price&#13;of $4.00 or more for the 
Company&amp;#146;s common stock has been sustained for five trading days. A

01to2012-07-31">&lt;p style="margin: 0pt"&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p 
style="font: 8pt/normal Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0"&gt;Except as 
disclosed, there are no pending legal proceedings&#13;against us that are 
expected to have a material adverse effect on our cash flows, financial 
condition or results of operations.&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 
8pt/normal Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 
0"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 8pt/normal Times New 
Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0"&gt;EMPLOYMENT 
AGREEMENTS&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 8pt/normal Times New Roman, 
Times, Serif; margin: 0"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 
8pt/normal Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0"&gt;On October 1, 2010, TMC 
signed an Employment Agreement with&#13;Gregory Schifrin (&amp;#147;Schifrin 
Agreement&amp;#148;), which agreement was acquired by WMTN as a result of the 
acquisition of TMC.&#13;Under the terms of the Schifrin Agreement, Mr. Schifrin 
was appointed Chief Executive Officer for an indefinite period at a 
salary&#13;of $120,000 per year. Mr. Schifrin is eligible for annual bonuses and
incentive plans as determined by the Company&amp;#146;s 
Compensation&#13;Committee. Mr. Schifrin is eligible for employee benefit 
programs, including 4 weeks of vacation per year, medical benefits and&#13;$500 
per day spent on the Company&amp;#146;s project sites. Mr. Schifrin may resign 
with 60 days' notice. If Mr. Schifrin is terminated&#13;without cause, including
a change in control (after six months), he is to receive in a lump sum, two 
times his annual salary, two&#13;times his targeted annual bonus, two times his 
last year&amp;#146;s bonus and any accrued vacation.&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p 
style="font: 8pt/normal Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 
0"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 8pt/normal Times New 
Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0"&gt;On October 1, 2010, TMC signed an Employment 
Agreement with&#13;James Baughman (&amp;#147;Baughman Agreement&amp;#148;), 
which agreement was acquired by WMTN as a result of the acquisition of 
TMC.&#13;Under the terms of the Baughman Agreement, Mr. Baughman was appointed 
Chief Operating Officer for an indefinite period at a salary&#13;of $120,000 per
year. Mr. Baughman is eligible for annual bonuses and incentive plans as 
determined by the Company&amp;#146;s Compensation&#13;Committee. Mr. Baughman is
eligible for employee benefit programs, including 4 weeks of vacation per year, 
medical benefits and&#13;$500 per day spent on the Company&amp;#146;s project 
sites. Mr. Baughman may resign with 60 days' notice. If Mr. Baughman is 
terminated&#13;without cause, including a change in control (after six months), 
he is to receive in a lump sum, two times his annual salary, two&#13;times his 
targeted annual bonus, two times his last year&amp;#146;s bonus and any accrued 
vacation.&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="margin: 
0pt"&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</us-gaap:LegalMattersAndContingenciesTextBlock>

}

border: 1px solid #acf;
}
/* Top labels */

background-color: #acf;
color: black;

text-align: center;
}

}

}

cursor: pointer;

}

}

}

}

}

}

}

}

border-bottom: 0px solid black;
}

}

}

      <tr>
        <th class="tl" colspan="1" rowspan="2">
          <div style="width: 200px;"><strong>3. Agreements<br></strong></div>
        </th>
        <th class="th" colspan="1">9 Months Ended</th>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <th class="th">
          <div>Jul. 31, 2012</div>
        </th>
      </tr>
      <tr class="re">
        <td class="pl" style="border-bottom: 0px;" valign="top"><a class="a" 
href="javascript:void(0);" onclick="top.Show.showAR( this, 'defref_us-
gaap_CommitmentsAndContingenciesDisclosureAbstract', 
window );"><strong>Commitments and Contingencies Disclosure 
[Abstract]</strong></a></td>
        <td class="text">&#xA0;<span></span></td>
      </tr>
      <tr class="ro">
        <td class="pl" style="border-bottom: 0px;" valign="top"><a class="a" 
href="javascript:void(0);" onclick="top.Show.showAR( this, 'defref_us-
gaap_CommitmentsDisclosureTextBlock', window );">3. Agreements</a></td>
        <td class="text"><p style="margin: 0pt"></p>
<p style="font: 8pt/normal Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 
0"><b>Exploration, Development and Mine Operating Agreements</b></p>
<p style="font: 8pt/normal Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0">&#160;</p>
<p style="font: 8pt/normal Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0"><b>Joint 
Venture Agreement</b></p>
<p style="font: 8pt/normal Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0">&#160;</p>
<p style="font: 8pt/normal Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0">On 
September 15, 2010, TMC and its wholly owned subsidiary,
TGC and Raven Gold Alaska, Inc. (&#147;Raven&#148;) signed an Exploration, 
Development and Mine Operating Agreement (&#147;JV
Agreement&#148;). TMC agreed to have 250,000 shares of WMTN common stock issued 
to Raven no later than one year after the closing
of the acquisition of TMC by WMTN and an additional 250,000 shares of WMTN 
common stock issued on or before each of December 31,
2011 and December 31, 2012. The $50,000 due with the signing of the Letter of 
Intent in February 2010 was paid September 17, 2010.
TMC has incurred $3,116,000 of project expenses through September 10, 2012 as 
defined by the JV Agreement.</p>
<p style="font: 8pt/normal Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0">&#160;</p>
<p style="font: 8pt/normal Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0">The JV 
Agreement has a term of twenty years, which can continue
longer as long as products are produced on a continuous basis and thereafter 
until all materials, equipment and infrastructure
are salvaged and disposed of, environmental compliance is completed and accepted
and the parties have completed a final accounting.
The JV Agreement defines terms and conditions where TMC and TGC earns a 51% 
interest with the following payments and stock issuances-</p>
<p style="font: 8pt/normal Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0">&#160;</p>
<p style="font: 8pt/normal Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0">Pay the 
following options payments:</p>
<p style="font: 8pt/normal Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0">&#160;</p>
<table cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" style="width: 100%">
<tr style="vertical-align: top">
    <td style="width: 10%; font: 8pt/115% Times New Roman, Times, Serif; text-
align: right">&#9679;&#160;&#160;</td>
    <td style="width: 90%; font: 8pt/115% Times New Roman, Times, Serif">Payment
of $10,000 with the signing of the Letter of Intent in February 2010 (paid 
September 2010).</td></tr>
<tr style="vertical-align: top">
    <td style="font: 8pt/115% Times New Roman, Times, Serif; text-align: 
right">&#9679;&#160;&#160;</td>
    <td style="font: 8pt/115% Times New Roman, Times, Serif">Payment of $40,000 
with the signing of the JV Agreement (paid September 2010).</td></tr>
</table>
<p style="font: 8pt/normal Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0">&#160;</p>
<table cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" style="font: 8pt Times New Roman, Times, 
Serif; width: 100%">
<tr style="vertical-align: top">
    <td style="width: 10%; line-height: 115%; text-align: 
right">&#9679;&#160;&#160;</td>
    <td style="width: 90%; line-height: 115%">Payment of $100,000 on or before 
December 31, 2011 (paid in December 2011).</td></tr>
<tr style="vertical-align: top">
    <td style="line-height: 115%; text-align: right">&#9679;&#160;&#160;</td>
    <td style="line-height: 115%">Payment of $150,000 on or before December 31, 
2012.</td></tr>
</table>
<p style="font: 8pt/normal Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0">&#160;</p>
<p style="font: 8pt/normal Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0">Provide the
following project funding-</p>
<p style="font: 8pt/normal Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0">&#160;</p>
<table cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" style="font: 8pt Times New Roman, Times, 
Serif; width: 100%">
<tr style="vertical-align: top">
    <td style="width: 10%; line-height: 115%; text-align: 
right">&#9679;&#160;&#160;</td>
    <td style="width: 90%; line-height: 115%">Payment of $1 million in project 
expenses on or before December 31, 2011, including $100,000 (paid) to Raven for 
camp equipment.&#160;</td></tr>
<tr style="vertical-align: top">
    <td style="line-height: 115%; text-align: right">&#9679;&#160;&#160;</td>
    <td style="line-height: 115%">Payment of $2.5 million in additional project 
expenses on or before December 31, 2012, including $100,000 to Raven for camp 
equipment.</td></tr>
</table>
<p style="font: 8pt/normal Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0">&#160;</p>
<table cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" style="font: 8pt Times New Roman, Times, 
Serif; width: 100%">
<tr style="vertical-align: top">
    <td style="width: 10%; line-height: 115%; text-align: 
right">&#9679;&#160;&#160;</td>
    <td style="width: 90%; line-height: 115%">Payment of $2.5 million in
additional project expenses on or before December 31, 2013.</td></tr>
</table>
<p style="font: 8pt/normal Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0">&#160;</p>
<p style="font: 8pt/normal Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0">Issue the 
following common stock, which is subject to a two
year trading restriction, upon the completion of the acquisition of TMC by 
WMTN:</p>
<p style="font: 8pt/normal Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0">&#160;</p>
<table cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" style="font: 8pt Times New Roman, Times, 
Serif; width: 100%">
<tr style="vertical-align: top">
    <td style="width: 10%; line-height: 115%; text-align: 
right">&#9679;&#160;&#160;</td>
    <td style="width: 90%; line-height: 115%">Issue 250,000 shares of WMTN 
common stock no later than one year after the closing of the acquisition of TMC 
(issued).</td></tr>
<tr style="vertical-align: top">
    <td style="line-height: 115%; text-align: right">&#9679;&#160;&#160;</td>
    <td style="line-height: 115%">Issue 250,000 shares of WMTN common stock on 
or before December 31, 2011 (issued), and December 31, 2012.</td></tr>
</table>
<p style="font: 8pt/normal Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0">&#160;</p>
<p style="font: 8pt/normal Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0">TMC and TGC
then can increase their interest to 80% in the
project with the following payments and stock issuances:</p>
<p style="font: 8pt/normal Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0">&#160;</p>
<table cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" style="font: 8pt Times New Roman, Times, 
Serif; width: 100%">
<tr style="vertical-align: top">
    <td style="width: 10%; line-height: 115%; text-align: 
right">&#9679;&#160;&#160;</td>
    <td style="width: 90%; line-height: 115%">Payment of $150,000 on or before 
December 31, 2013.</td></tr>
<tr style="vertical-align: top">
    <td style="line-height: 115%; text-align: right">&#9679;&#160;&#160;</td>
    <td style="line-height: 115%">Payment of $3.05 million in additional project
expenses on or before December 31, 2014.</td></tr>
</table>
<p style="font: 8pt/normal Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0">&#160;</p>
<table cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" style="font: 8pt Times New Roman, Times, 
Serif; width: 100%">
<tr style="vertical-align: top">
    <td style="width: 10%; line-height: 115%; text-align: 
right">&#9679;&#160;&#160;</td>
    <td style="width: 90%; line-height: 115%">Issue 250,000 shares of WMTN 
common stock on or before December 31, 2014.</td></tr>
</table>
<p style="font: 8pt/normal Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0">&#160;</p>
<p style="font: 8pt/normal Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0">The failure
to operate in accordance with the JV Agreement
could result in the Company&#146;s interest in the JV being revoked or the JV 
Agreement being terminated.</p>
<p style="font: 8pt/normal Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0">&#160;</p>
<p style="font: 8pt/normal Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0">All costs
related to the JV Agreement have been recorded as
exploration expenses.&#160;&#160;The Company has not earned its 51% interest in 
the joint venture and does not control the joint
venture therefore, the joint venture is not consolidated in the Company&#146;s 
financial statements. At such time as the Company
earns its 51% or gains control of the joint venture, it will consolidate the 
operations of the joint venture.&#160;</p>
<p style="font: 8pt/normal Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0">&#160;</p>
<p style="font: 8pt/normal Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0"><b>Amended 
Claims Agreement with Ben Porterfield</b></p>
<p style="font: 8pt/normal Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0">&#160;</p>
<p style="font: 8pt/normal Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0">On January 
7, 2011, TMC entered into an Amended Claims Agreement
with Ben Porterfield related to five mining claims known as Fish Creek 1-5 (ADL-
648383 through ADL-648387), which claims have been
assigned to the Terra Project. As part of this Amended Claims Agreement, Ben 
Porterfield consented to certain conveyances, assignments,
contributions and transfers related to this above five mining claims.</p>
<p style="font: 8pt/normal Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0">&#160;</p>
<p style="font: 8pt/normal Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0">The Amended
Lease Agreement, which incorporates the Lease
dated March 22, 2005 and the September 27, 2010 Consent between Ben Porterfield 
and AngloGold Ashanti (USA) Exploration Inc., has
a term of ten years, which can be extended for an additional ten years with 
thirty days written notice. The Amended Lease Agreement
defines terms and conditions and requires the following minimum royalties:</p>
<p style="font: 8pt/normal Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0">&#160;</p>
<table cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" style="font: 8pt Times New Roman, Times, 
Serif; width: 100%">
<tr style="vertical-align: top">
    <td style="width: 10%; line-height: 115%; text-align: 
right">&#9679;&#160;&#160;</td>
    <td style="width: 90%; line-height: 115%">Payment of $100,000 annually on 
March 22, 2011 (paid).&#160;</td></tr>
<tr style="vertical-align: top">
    <td style="line-height: 115%; text-align: right">&#9679;&#160;&#160;</td>
    <td style="line-height: 115%">Payment of $100,000 annually on March 22, 2012
(paid) through March 22, 2015.</td></tr>
</table>
<p style="font: 8pt/normal Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0">&#160;</p>
<table cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" style="font: 8pt Times New Roman, Times, 
Serif; width: 100%">
<tr style="vertical-align: top">
    <td style="width: 10%; line-height: 115%; text-align: 
right">&#9679;&#160;&#160;</td>
    <td style="width: 90%; line-height: 115%">Payment of $125,000 annually on 
March 22, 2016 through the termination of the Amended Claims 
Agreement.</td></tr>
</table>
<p style="font: 8pt/normal Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0">&#160;</p>
<p style="font: 8pt/normal Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0">The Company
can terminate the Amended Lease Agreement with
the payment of $875,000, less $75,000 paid during the years 2006-2011<i>. 
</i>The payment maybe paid over three annual payments.</p>
<p style="font: 8pt/normal Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0">&#160;</p>
<p style="font: 8pt/normal Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0">TMC has 
paid in total $250,000 to Ben Porterfield and WMTN
issued 500,000 shares of WMTN restricted common stock on March 23, 2011. The 
common stock was recorded as Contractual Rights at
$250,000 or $.50 per share. Mr. Porterfield is to receive 200 tons of Bens Vein 
materials over the next two years. The investment
in the exclusive rights to the mineral properties is accounted for at 
cost.&#160;As of July 31, 2012, the Company has capitalized
$550,000 related to this Claims Agreement.</p>
<p style="font: 8pt/normal Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0">&#160;</p>
<p style="font: 8pt/normal Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0">The Amended
Lease Agreement, which incorporates the Lease
dated March 22, 2005, provides for a production royalty of 4% of the net smelter
return for all minerals produced or sold. The
Company may repurchase 1% of the production royalty right for $1,000,000 and an 
additional 1% for $3,000,000.</p>
<p style="font: 8pt/normal Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0">&#160;</p>
<p style="font: 8pt/normal Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0">The failure
to operate in accordance with the Amended Lease
or Lease Agreements could result in the Lease being terminated.&#160;</p>
<p style="margin: 0pt"></p><span></span></td>
      </tr>
    </table>

Definition</a><div>
                <p>The entire disclosure for significant arrangements with third
parties, which includes operating lease arrangements and arrangements in which 
the entity has agreed to expend funds to procure goods or services, or has 
agreed to commit resources to supply goods or services, and operating lease 
arrangements. Descriptions may include identification of the specific goods and 
services, period of time covered, minimum quantities and amounts, and 
cancellation rights.</p>

        <tr>
          <td>
            <div class="body" style="padding: 2px;"><a 
href="javascript:void(0);" onclick="top.Show.toggleNext( this );">- 
Definition</a><div>
                <p>Sum of the carrying values as of the balance sheet date of 
obligations incurred through that date and due within one year (or the operating
cycle, if longer), including liabilities incurred (and for which invoices have 
typically been received) and payable to vendors for goods and services received,
taxes, interest, rent and utilities, accrued salaries and bonuses, payroll taxes
and fringe benefits.</p>

      <table border="0" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" class="authRefData" 
style="display: none;" id="defref_us-gaap_AdditionalPaidInCapital">
        <tr>
          <td class="hide"><a style="color: white;" href="javascript:void(0);" 
onclick="top.Show.hideAR();">X</a></td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>
            <div class="body" style="padding: 2px;"><a 
href="javascript:void(0);" onclick="top.Show.toggleNext( this );">- 
Definition</a><div>
<p>Excess of issue price over par or stated value of the 
entity's capital stock and amounts received from other transactions involving 
the entity's stock or stockholders. Includes adjustments to additional paid in 
capital. Some examples of such adjustments include recording the issuance of 
debt with a beneficial conversion feature and certain tax consequences of equity
instruments awarded to employees. Use this element for the aggregate amount of 
additional paid-in capital associated with common and preferred stock. For 
additional paid-in capital associated with only common stock, use the element 
additional paid in capital, common stock. For additional paid-in capital 
associated with only preferred stock, use the element additional paid in 
capital, preferred stock.</p>
              </div><a href="javascript:void(0);" 
onclick="top.Show.toggleNext( this );">+ References</a><div style="display: 
none;">

        <tr>
          <td>
            <div class="body" style="padding: 2px;"><a 
href="javascript:void(0);" onclick="top.Show.toggleNext( this );">- 
Definition</a><div>
                <p>Amount of currency on hand as well as demand deposits with 
banks or financial institutions. Includes other kinds of accounts that have the 
general characteristics of demand deposits. Also includes short-term, highly 
liquid investments that are both readily convertible to known amounts of cash 
and so near their maturity that they present insignificant risk of changes in 
value because of changes in interest rates. Excludes cash and cash equivalents 
within disposal group and discontinued operation.</p>

        <tr>
          <td class="hide"><a style="color: white;" href="javascript:void(0);" 
onclick="top.Show.hideAR();">X</a></td>

        <tr>
          <td>
            <div class="body" style="padding: 2px;"><a 
href="javascript:void(0);" onclick="top.Show.toggleNext( this );">- 
Definition</a><div>
                <p>Represents the caption on the face of the balance sheet to 
indicate that the entity has entered into (1) purchase or supply arrangements 
that will require expending a portion of its resources to meet the terms 
thereof, and (2) is exposed to potential losses or, less frequently, gains, 
arising from (a) possible claims against a company's resources due to future 
performance under contract terms, and (b) possible losses or likely gains from 
uncertainties that will ultimately be resolved when one or more future events 
that are deemed likely to occur do occur or fail to occur.</p>

          <td class="hide"><a style="color: white;" href="javascript:void(0);"

          <td>
            <div class="body" style="padding: 2px;"><a 
href="javascript:void(0);" onclick="top.Show.toggleNext( this );">- 
Definition</a><div>
                <p>Aggregate par or stated value of issued nonredeemable common 
stock (or common stock redeemable solely at the option of the issuer). This item
includes treasury stock repurchased by the entity. Note: elements for number of 
nonredeemable common shares, par value and other disclosure concepts are in 
another section within stockholders' equity.</p>

href="javascript:void(0);" onclick="top.Show.toggleNext( this );">- 
Definition</a><div>
                <p>Aggregate carrying amount, as of the balance sheet date, of 
current assets not separately disclosed in the balance sheet. Current assets are
expected to be realized or consumed within one year (or the normal operating 
cycle, if longer).</p>

          <td>
            <div class="body" style="padding: 2px;"><a 
href="javascript:void(0);" onclick="top.Show.toggleNext( this );">- 
Definition</a><div>
                <p>Aggregate carrying amount of current liabilities (due within 
one year or within the normal operating cycle if longer) not separately 
disclosed in the balance sheet. Includes costs that are statutory in nature, are
incurred on contractual obligations, or accumulate over time and for which 
invoices have not yet been received or will not be rendered and of liabilities 
not separately disclosed.</p>

          <td>
            <div class="body" style="padding: 2px;"><a 
href="javascript:void(0);" onclick="top.Show.toggleNext( this );">- 
Definition</a><div>
                <p>Sum of the carrying amount for an unclassified balance sheet 
date of expenditures made in advance of when the economic benefit of the cost 
will be realized, and which will be expensed in future periods with the passage 
of time or when a triggering event occurs and the carrying amount as of the 
balance sheet date of assets not otherwise specified in the taxonomy. Also 
includes assets not individually reported in the financial statements, or not 
separately disclosed in notes.</p>

                <p>Amount, net of accumulated depreciation, depletion and 
amortization, of long-lived physical assets used in the normal conduct of 
business and not intended for resale. Examples include, but are not limited to, 
land, buildings, machinery and equipment, office equipment, furniture and 
fixtures, and computer equipment.</p>

              </div>
            </div>

          <td>
            <div class="body" style="padding: 2px;"><a

Definition</a><div>
                <p>Reflects the total carrying amount as of the balance sheet 
date of debt having initial terms less than one year or the normal operating 
cycle, if longer.</p>

      <table border="0" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" class="authRefData"

        <tr>
          <td class="hide"><a style="color: white;" href="javascript:void(0);"

        <tr>
          <td>
            <div class="body" style="padding: 2px;"><a 
href="javascript:void(0);" onclick="top.Show.toggleNext( this );">-
Definition</a><div>
                <p>Total of all stockholders' equity (deficit) items, net of 
receivables from officers, directors, owners, and affiliates of the entity which
are attributable to the parent. The amount of the economic entity's 
stockholders' equity attributable to the parent excludes the amount of 
stockholders' equity which is allocable to that ownership interest in subsidiary
equity which is not attributable to the parent (noncontrolling interest, 
minority interest). This excludes temporary equity and is sometimes called 
permanent equity.</p>
